## New for this step: a live Ruby↔Python translation trap already caught

`to_payload`'s new `tools:` parameter uses Ruby's `tools.nil? ? to_tools(context.tools) : tools`
— an explicit nil-check, not a truthy check. This matters *a lot* here:
`Agent#wrap_up` calls `client.call(tools: [], ...)` specifically to send
an *empty* tools array (disabling tool use for the wind-down call). A
naive Python `tools or self.to_tools(context.tools)` would treat `[]` as
falsy and silently ignore the override, defeating the entire wrap-up
mechanism. Every `to_payload` in every backend uses
`self.to_tools(context.tools) if tools is None else tools` — the
established Ruby-`||`-vs-Python-`or` gotcha, this time concretely load-
bearing rather than a hypothetical.

## New for this step: the actual point of it — response normalization + the loop

Five providers, five different tool-call response shapes (Anthropic nests
in `content`, Ollama/OpenAI put them in `message.tool_calls`/
`choices[0].message.tool_calls`, Gemini calls them `functionCall` parts).
Every backend now implements `parse_response(response)`, converting its
raw response into one common shape:

```python
{
    "stop_reason": "tool_use" | "end_turn",
    "content": [
        {"type": "text", "text": "..."},
        {"type": "tool_use", "id": "...", "name": "...", "input": {...}},
    ],
}
```

`Agent` only ever sees this shape. The conversion also runs in reverse:
when conversation history replays on the next request, Ollama, OllamaCloud,
OpenAI, and Gemini each rebuild a provider-specific assistant message from
the normalized content via a private `assistant_message`/`assistant_parts`
method (the inverse of `parse_response`). **Anthropic needs no inverse** —
its `content` array doubles as both the normalized shape and its own wire
format, so an assistant `Message`'s `content` (a list of blocks) passes
straight through unchanged in `to_messages`'s `else` branch.

Tool call IDs aren't universal: Anthropic and OpenAI assign a real `id`;
Ollama, OllamaCloud, and Gemini don't, so those backends reuse the tool's
`name` as its `id` and match `tool_result` back to the call by name — port
this as-is, it's an intentional per-provider difference, not a bug.

